A helix has equation {eq}\displaystyle{ r(t)=\frac{\langle 4\sin(t), 5, 4\cos(t)\rangle}{\sqrt{41}}}

{/eq}. At the point {eq}\displaystyle{(x,y,z)=\left(\frac{4\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{41}},5,\frac{4\sqrt{39}}{\sqrt{41}}\right)}

{/eq}, what is the {eq}\displaystyle{z}

{/eq} -component of {eq}\displaystyle{r''(t)}

{/eq}? Find it using the Chain Rule.
If {eq}\vec{r(t)} = \ang 4\sin t, 5, 4 \cos t \ang/\sqrt{41}

{/eq}, then {eq}\vec{r''(t)} = \ang \frac{-4}{\sqrt{41}}\cos t, 0, 5\frac{-4}{\sqrt{41}}\sin t \ang

{/eq}, so the {eq}\sin

{/eq} term is the  {eq}z

{/eq} component of {eq}\vec{r''(t)}

{/eq}.
We have that the helix satisfies

{eq}\begin{align*}

\frac{4\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{41}} &= \frac{4\sin t}{\sqrt{41}} \\

\frac{4\sqrt{39}}{\sqrt{41}} &= \frac{4\cos t}{\sqrt{41}}

\end{align*}

{/eq}

This means {eq}t

{/eq} is in a reference triangle where
{eq}\begin{align*}

\tan t &= \sqrt{\frac{39}{2}} \\

t &= \tan^{-1} \sqrt{\frac{39}{2}}

\end{align*}

{/eq}
Therefore {eq}\sin t = \dfrac{\sqrt{78}}{7}

{/eq}, and so

{eq}\begin{align*}

\frac{dr''(t)}{dz} &= 5 \times \left( \frac{-4}{\sqrt{41}}\sin t \right) \\

